# History of Linux

## What is Linux?

Linux is an open-source operating system kernel created by Linus Torvalds in 1991. Today, Linux powers servers, cloud platforms, smartphones, supercomputers, and embedded devices worldwide.

---

## Before Linux: UNIX (1969)

The story of Linux begins with Unix, developed in 1969 at Bell Labs by researchers including Ken Thompson and Dennis Ritchie.

UNIX introduced many concepts still used today:

* Multi-user systems
* Multitasking
* File permissions
* Hierarchical file system
* Shell scripting

---

## GNU Project (1983)

In 1983, Richard Stallman launched the GNU Project to create a free UNIX-like operating system.

GNU developed many essential tools:

* GCC Compiler
* Bash Shell
* Core Utilities
* Text Editors

However, GNU lacked a complete kernel.

---

## Birth of Linux (1991)

In 1991, a 21-year-old Finnish computer science student, Linus Torvalds, started developing a kernel as a hobby.

On August 25, 1991, he posted a message on the Usenet group comp.os.minix:

> "I'm doing a free operating system (just a hobby, won't be big and professional like GNU)..."

This project became Linux.

---

## Linux Version 0.01 (1991)

The first Linux release:

* Released in September 1991
* Around 10,000 lines of code
* Supported Intel 80386 processors
* Required technical expertise to install

---

## GNU + Linux = Complete Operating System

Linux provided the kernel, while GNU provided system tools.

Together they formed a complete operating system often referred to as:

* Linux
* GNU/Linux

---

## Linux Goes Open Source (1992)

In 1992, Linux was released under the GNU General Public License (GPL).

This allowed anyone to:

* View source code
* Modify it
* Redistribute it

This decision accelerated Linux adoption worldwide.

---

## Rise of Linux Distributions

Different organizations combined the Linux kernel with software packages to create distributions.

Popular distributions include:

* Debian (1993)
* Red Hat Enterprise Linux
* Ubuntu
* Fedora Linux
* CentOS
* SUSE Linux Enterprise

---

## Linux in Servers (1990s–2000s)

Linux became the preferred server operating system because it was:

* Stable
* Secure
* Free
* Highly customizable

Many internet companies adopted Linux for web hosting and infrastructure.

---

## Linux Powers the Cloud

Today, most cloud platforms use Linux:

* Amazon Web Services
* Microsoft Azure
* Google Cloud

More than 90% of cloud workloads run on Linux-based systems.

---

## Linux and Android

In 2008, Android was released using the Linux kernel.

Today Android is the world's most widely used mobile operating system.

---

## Linux Today

Linux powers:

* Web servers
* Cloud infrastructure
* Supercomputers
* Smartphones
* IoT devices
* Containers and Kubernetes platforms

Major companies contributing to Linux include:

* IBM
* Intel
* Google
* Microsoft
* Red Hat

---

## Linux Timeline

| Year    | Event                                       |
| ------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| 1969    | UNIX created at Bell Labs                   |
| 1983    | GNU Project started                         |
| 1991    | Linux kernel created by Linus Torvalds      |
| 1992    | Linux released under GPL                    |
| 1993    | Debian released                             |
| 1994    | Linux Kernel 1.0 released                   |
| 2004    | Ubuntu released                             |
| 2008    | Android released                            |
| 2014    | Kubernetes introduced                       |
| Present | Linux dominates cloud computing and servers |

### Interview Answer (Short Version)

**"Linux is an open-source UNIX-like operating system kernel created by Linus Torvalds in 1991. It was combined with GNU tools to form a complete operating system. Due to its stability, security, flexibility, and open-source nature, Linux became widely used in servers, cloud computing, supercomputers, and Android devices. Today it is one of the most important operating systems in the world."**
